summary.dataset_description: A dataset containing four sets of data with nearly identical statistical properties, demonstrating the importance of visualizing data.

goals.question: What is the relationship between X and Y in each of the four data sets?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of X vs Y for each data set
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the correlation between X and Y in each data set and identify any patterns or outliers.

goals.question: What is the mean and standard deviation of X and Y in each data set?
goals.visualization: box plot of X and Y for each data set
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us compare the central tendency and variability of X and Y in each data set and identify any differences or similarities.

goals.question: What is the distribution of X and Y in each data set?
goals.visualization: histogram of X and Y for each data set
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the frequency and spread of X and Y in each data set and identify any skewness or outliers.

goals.question: What is the correlation coefficient between X and Y in each data set?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of X vs Y with correlation coefficient and regression line for each data set
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us quantify the strength and direction of the linear relationship between X and Y in each data set and identify any deviations from the regression line.

goals.question: What is the difference between the four data sets in terms of X and Y?
goals.visualization: parallel coordinate plot of X and Y for each data set
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us compare the values of X and Y in each data set and identify any differences or similarities across multiple variables.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.scatterplot(data=data, x='X', y='Y', hue='Series', palette='deep')
    plt.title("What is the relationship between X and Y in each of the four data sets?", wrap=True)
    plt.legend(title='Series')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Series'] = pd.Categorical(data['Series'])
    melted_data = data.melt(id_vars=['Series'], value_vars=['X', 'Y'], var_name='Variable', value_name='Value')
    chart = sns.boxplot(x='Series', y='Value', hue='Variable', data=melted_data)
    plt.title("What is the mean and standard deviation of X and Y in each data set?", wrap=True)
    plt.legend(title='Variable')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    g = sns.FacetGrid(data, col="Series", hue="Series", col_wrap=2)
    g.map_dataframe(sns.histplot, x="X", element="step", alpha=0.5)
    g.map_dataframe(sns.histplot, x="Y", element="step", alpha=0.5)
    g.add_legend(title="Series")
    plt.title("What is the distribution of X and Y in each data set?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Series'] = data['Series'].astype('category')
    g = sns.FacetGrid(data, col="Series", hue="Series", col_wrap=2, height=4)
    g.map(sns.regplot, "X", "Y", ci=None, robust=True)
    
    for ax, series in zip(g.axes.flat, data['Series'].cat.categories):
        corr_coef = np.corrcoef(data[data['Series'] == series]['X'], data[data['Series'] == series]['Y'])[0, 1]
        ax.set_title(f"Series {series}: Correlation Coefficient = {corr_coef:.2f}")
    
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
    g.fig.suptitle("What is the correlation coefficient between X and Y in each data set?")
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
